      • addEventListener

        public SchedulerState addEventListener(SchedulerEventListener arg0,
                                       boolean arg1,
                                       boolean arg2,
                                       SchedulerEvent... arg3)
                                throws NotConnectedException,
                                       PermissionException
        Description copied from interface: Scheduler
        Add a scheduler event Listener. this listener provides method to notice of new coming job, started task, finished task, running job, finished job, etc...

        You may use this method once by remote or active object.
        Every call to this method will remove your previous listening settings.
        If you want to get 2 type of events, add the 2 events type you want at the end of this method. If no type is specified, all of them will be sent.

        If you want to received the events concerning your job only, just set the 'myEventsOnly' parameter to true. otherwise, you will received events coming from any user.

        Specified by:
        addEventListener in interface Scheduler
        Parameters:
        arg0 - a SchedulerEventListener on which the scheduler will talk.
        arg1 - a boolean that indicates if you want to receive every events or just those concerning your jobs. This won't affect the scheduler state event that will be sent anyway.
        arg2 - if false, this method returns null, if true, it returns the Scheduler current state.
        arg3 - An array of events that you want to receive from the scheduler.
        Returns:
        the scheduler current state containing the different lists of jobs if the getInitialState parameter is true, null if false.
        Throws:
        NotConnectedException - if you are not authenticated.
        PermissionException - if you can't access this particular job.

      • getState

        public SchedulerState getState()
                        throws NotConnectedException,
                               PermissionException
        Description copied from interface: Scheduler
        Get the list of job states that describe every jobs in the Scheduler. The SchedulerState contains 3 list of jobs, pending, running, and finished. Every jobs will be returned depending on your right.

        If a PermissionException is thrown, try using Scheduler.getState(boolean) method with argument true. NOTE: the total list of finished jobs is limited by the Java property 'scheduler.state.max.finished.jobs' configured on the server. Default is 1000 finished jobs.

        Specified by:
        getState in interface Scheduler
        Returns:
        the list of every jobs in the Scheduler
        Throws:
        NotConnectedException - if you are not authenticated.
        PermissionException - if you can't access this particular method.

      • getState

        public SchedulerState getState(boolean arg0)
                        throws NotConnectedException,
                               PermissionException
        Description copied from interface: Scheduler
        Get the list of job states that describe every jobs in the Scheduler. The SchedulerState contains 3 list of jobs, pending, running, and finished If the given argument is true, only job that you own will be returned, otherwise every jobs will be returned depending on your right. NOTE: the total list of finished jobs is limited by the Java property 'scheduler.state.max.finished.jobs' configured on the server. Default is 1000 finished jobs. From this list, only jobs belonging to the current user will be returned.
        Specified by:
        getState in interface Scheduler
        Parameters:
        arg0 - true to get only my jobs, false to get any.
        Returns:
        the list of every jobs in the Scheduler
        Throws:
        NotConnectedException - if you are not authenticated.
        PermissionException - if you can't access this particular method.

      • getTaskResultFromIncarnation

        public TaskResult getTaskResultFromIncarnation(JobId arg0,
                                               String arg1,
                                               int arg2)
                                        throws NotConnectedException,
                                               UnknownJobException,
                                               UnknownTaskException,
                                               PermissionException
        Description copied from interface: Scheduler
        Get the result for the given task name and the given incarnation in the given jobId.

        A user can only get HIS result back.

        The incarnation argument represents the task result to get. If the task has failed 3 times and then has worked, then 0 represents the last result, 1 the previous, ..., and 3 represents the result of the first execution.

        If the job does not exist, a schedulerException is sent with the proper message.

        So, if you have the right to get the task result that is in the job represented by the given jobId and if the job and task name exist, so you will receive the result. In any other cases a schedulerException will be thrown.

        Specified by:
        getTaskResultFromIncarnation in interface Scheduler
        Parameters:
        arg0 - the job in which the task result is.
        arg1 - the name of the task in which the result is.
        arg2 - id of incarnation (0 is the last one, 1 the previous, and so on...)
        Returns:
        a job Result containing information about the result. If null is returned, this task is not yet terminated or not available.
        Throws:
        NotConnectedException - if you are not authenticated.
        UnknownJobException - if the job does not exist.
        UnknownTaskException - if this task does not exist in the job.
        PermissionException - if you can't access this particular job.

      • getTaskResultAllIncarnations

        public List<TaskResult> getTaskResultAllIncarnations(JobId arg0,
                                                     String arg1)
                                              throws NotConnectedException,
                                                     UnknownJobException,
                                                     UnknownTaskException,
                                                     PermissionException
        Description copied from interface: Scheduler
        Get the result for the given task name and all result incarnations in the given jobId.

        This method returns a list of task result attempts. If the task has failed 3 times and then has worked, then the list will contain a list of 4 task results. 0 represents the first failed result attempt, 1 the next one, ..., and 3 represents the result of the last execution. In that sense the id order is reversed comparing to individual calls to getTaskResultFromIncarnation

        Specified by:
        getTaskResultAllIncarnations in interface Scheduler
        Parameters:
        arg0 - the job in which the task result is.
        arg1 - the name of the task in which the result is.
        Returns:
        a list of Task Results containing information about the result. If the returned list is empty, this task is not yet terminated or not available.
        Throws:
        NotConnectedException - if you are not authenticated.
        UnknownJobException - if the job does not exist.
        UnknownTaskException - if this task does not exist in the job.
        PermissionException - if you can't access this particular job.

        Get the result for the given task name and the given incarnation in the given jobId. The jobId is given as a string. It's in fact the string returned by the JobId.value() method. In any other cases a schedulerException will be thrown.

      • reloadPolicyConfiguration

        public boolean reloadPolicyConfiguration()
                                  throws NotConnectedException,
                                         PermissionException
        Description copied from interface: Scheduler
        For administrator only, order a reload to the policy.

        The default behavior reload the configuration file and update the properties available in policy. This will cause the Policy#reloadConfig() method to be called. This last method can be overridden in the policy to perform a custom behavior on reload.

        Specified by:
        reloadPolicyConfiguration in interface Scheduler
        Returns:
        true if success, false otherwise.
